(94, 1, '2018-02-18 14:52:37', '2018-02-18 14:52:37', '<div class="excerpt">\r\n\r\n#1: you don\'t have to know how to code. But wait! Donâ€™t dismiss your idea purely because you donâ€™t have any development experience â€“ not every tech start-up founder can code, and thatâ€™s okay.\r\n\r\nTake Airbnb, for example. Today itâ€™s a billion-dollar company, but neither of its founders had programming experience when they originally came up with the concept. From product validation to market fit and customer engagement, thereâ€™s plenty for a self-confessed ideas person or designer to do. So if you think you could be sitting on the next Snapchat but donâ€™t know what launching an app might involve, read on.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<section class="entry-content cf">\r\n<h2>1) You can outsource the techy bits</h2>\r\nAs weâ€™ve already established, the ability to code isnâ€™t necessarily a dealbreaker. However, you could make life a lot easier for yourself by saddling up with a technical co-founder. But if youâ€™re hellbent on keeping all the glory (and work) for yourself, you will need to enlist the services of a developer, so ask around for some recommendations. For <a href="http://www.cinderly.com/">Cinderly</a> co-founders Luke Stoffel and Laura von Holt â€“ neither of whom have programming experience â€“ they knew immediately that they wanted Australian developer David McKinney (the brains behind Emoji Type) to build their app, which helps users filter fashion finds, has been billed as the first data-driven style app of its kind. â€œDavid was twice our budget, but like all internet love stories, we figured it out,â€ says Laura.\r\n<h3><strong>2) Someoneâ€™s probably already thought of it</strong></h3>\r\nThere are currently over two million apps available on the App Store, so the chances of you coming up with an entirely new concept isnâ€™t all that likely. But fret not, boasting strong similarities to another app doesnâ€™t mean you have to go back to the drawing board. Ultimately, it all comes down to the execution. What if Facebook had bowed out before it had even begun because MySpace was already on the scene? If you think thereâ€™s a way to make it better, go forth and build. Or, you know, pay someone else to build.\r\n<h4><strong>3) Establish who your app caters to</strong></h4>\r\nApps can beÂ divided into three groups: apps that are born out of need, apps that generally make life easier and apps that are purely there for entertainment.\r\n\r\nâ€œReally think through the whole app from your userâ€™s point of view,â€ advises Laura. â€œWhat will it be like for them to use it, and where in their life do you fit in? For us, we realised it was a viable idea based on our own experiences of shopping in stores and online,â€ she says of the moment that she knew Cinderly had the potential to make the sometimes-arduous process of finding beautiful clothes that fit well easier.\r\n<h5><strong>4) There will be a <em>lot</em> of testing involved</strong></h5>\r\nAnd retesting. And possibly some more retesting. <a href="http://www.cinderly.com/">Cinderly</a> rolled out a soft launch around six months ago and has since been gathering information and feedback from users. TheÂ makers are currently in the process of refining the app before rolling out a new updated version in 2017. â€œWe want to make Cinderly like the Pokemon Go of retail â€“ a â€˜Mall Madnessâ€™ game for the digital age,â€ says Laura.\r\n<h6><strong>5) It might not work out</strong></h6>\r\nBefore you throw all of your energy into your app, you need to acknowledge that it mightnâ€™t be the resounding success that you dream it could be. If itâ€™s not, you wouldnâ€™t be alone. In fact, statistics show that as few as 11% of all apps created sell over the elusive 50,000 mark. And yet, if you really believe in your idea and are willing to be brave, put in the groundwork â€“ who knows where it could lead?\r\n\r\nLike the eye of a tornado, weâ€™re living slap-bang in the middle of the â€˜Thereâ€™s an app for thatâ€™ age. So if you havenâ€™t already flirted with the idea of launching your own app, youâ€™ve almost certainly had a fleeting idea for one before (probably) tossing it into the â€˜too hardâ€™ basket.\r\n\r\n</section>', '5 things you should know before launching your own app', 'Vestibulum vel aliquam nisl. Integer dignissim lorem vitae ligula tincidunt, nec sollicitudin magna suscipit. Sed tempor vulputate ornare. Duis quis sagittis dolor, id imperdiet lacus. Phasellus tincidunt ipsum augue.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '23-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-02-18 14:52:37', '2018-02-18 14:52:37', '', 23, 'http://localhost:8888/23-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(95, 1, '2018-02-18 14:52:57', '2018-02-18 14:52:57', 'â€œEven though I loved working there and had a perfect-on-paper role myself, something was still missing,â€ Jenny â€“ who co-founded the Career Guru program at the internet search giant â€“ explains in her new book <em>PIVOT: The Only Move That Matters is Your Next One. </em>â€œPeople reacted as if I were breaking up with Brad Pitt. â€˜You really think you can do better than Gooooogle?!â€™â€ she recalls. â€œI wasnâ€™t so sure, but I knew I would forever regret not trying.â€\r\n\r\nAdjusting â€“ or <em>pivoting</em> â€“ our career trajectories has become a necessary evil for Millennials, who struggle to forge a concrete career path during this age of uncertainty. â€œWe can expect to experience significant changes every few years, much more often than was socially acceptable in the past. People are no longer working at the same jobs for forty years with the safety of pensions waiting at the end,â€ explains Jenny, who cites the advancement of technology as the culprit. â€œThe average employee tenure is now four to five years and job roles often change dramatically within those four to five years. Among workers twenty-five to thirty-four years old, the average tenure drops to three years.â€\r\n<blockquote>However, instead of fearing it, Jenny urges us to embrace this accelerated pace of change. â€œYou can learn to enjoy calculated risk and uncertainty in exchange for adventure, flexibility, freedom, and opportunity,â€ she writes.<strong>Â </strong></blockquote>\r\n<h2><strong>Pivot or be pivoted</strong></h2>\r\nA career pivot is executed in four stages; plant, scan, pilot and launch. â€œI define a career pivot as doubling down on what is working to make a purposeful shift in a new, related direction,â€ writes Jenny, who advises using your existing base of strengths and experience as leverage. â€œI have worked with people of all ages and career stages. Those who are most successful give themselves permission to explore continually, improving how quickly they spot their next move.â€\r\n<h2><strong>Forget the five year plan</strong></h2>\r\nMuch can happen within the job economy over the course of the next five years so instead of hatching a five-year plan, make it a 12-month one. â€œThe days of mapping an entire career path are over. You do not have to specify the details of your life five moves or five years out,â€ writes Jenny. â€œConsider what you were doing five years ago. Did you have any idea where you would be today?â€\r\n\r\nInstead, take a retrospective look at your work history and make note of any career pivots you have already made, urges Jenny. â€œBy learning how to connect the dots looking backward <em>and then </em>forward, we can get better at making career connections in real time, not waiting too long until we are burned out, unhappy and forced to make a change.â€\r\n<h2>Ditch the concept of the career ladder</h2>\r\nâ€œCareers are no longer straightforward, linear, and predictable like ladders. They are now much more like smartphones,â€ writes Jenny, who continues the analogy by advising us to download the â€˜appsâ€™ â€“ for skills and interests, etc. â€“ we need in order to feel fulfilled. While investing in one â€˜appâ€™ may seem like a risk, Jenny suggests downloading a series of smaller ones simultaneously. For example, study a subject in your spare time rather than quitting your job and re-entering full time education. â€œYou can reduce risk, experiment with ideas, and enhance your career operating system without sending yourself into a panic by trying to make moves that are too drastic, too far removed from what you are doing now.â€\r\n<h2><strong>Donâ€™t do anything drastic</strong></h2>\r\nFinally, Jenny urges us to carefully consider each move we make. â€œThis book is not a rallying cry for quitting your job and fighting â€˜The Man,â€™â€ she maintains, adding that choosing the opportune time to strategically change jobs is the key. â€œNor is this book a caution to stay out, shackled by golden handcuffs, if you have hit a career plateau.â€', 'Why your next career move is the only one that matters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-02-18 14:52:57', '2018-02-18 14:52:57', '', 1, 'http://localhost:8888/1-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
